 Lancashire, Durham, and many other counties), themselves from Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade, clearing’.","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Langlif</i> (Old Norse <i>Langlíf</i> ‘long’ + ‘life’ or ‘body’).","Americanized form of French   Langlais  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Langlais","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Marcel, Normand, Albertine, Armand, Cecile, Enoil, Herve, Jacques, Laurent.","French: ethnic name for an Englishman, from <i>Anglais</i> ‘Englishman’, with fused definite article <i>l'</i>. Compare   Langley  .","History: Daniel Sargent <i>dit</i> Sérien and Langlais from Worcester, MA married Marguerite Lavoie in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1718. Joseph Weber <i>dit</i> Langlais from Boston, MA married Marie-Charlotte Guillet in Cap Saint-Ignace, QC, in 1725."]},{"name":"Longley","meanings":["English (mainly Nottinghamshire and South Yorkshire): variant of   Langley  . Compare   Longpre   2."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Langley was born in 1379, in Shipton-under-Wychwood, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married John de Ver